I made similar paint-swirled ornaments like the ones in the main photo (many years ago), & I remember the key being that you rinse the inside of the ornament first with a solution of vinegar & water. They were amazing & I have wanted to do it again since.
Do you remember the ratio of water to vinegar?  May have to google this!

I just googled it to find out, & the instructions I saw just said to swirl a little vinegar or rubbing alcohol in them, then pour it out & let the inside dry before adding paint. I didn't remember that part but it sounds right. So I'd just use straight vinegar. I could've sworn it was vinegar & water, but maybe using it straight gives better results. :)
I think doing it straight strips any oils better inside the ornaments - you're basically trying to clean them out and de-glaze the inside so the paint sticks.

You're right, I read that it helps keep the paint from cracking/peeling over time.  I found that the paint spread much easier after rinsing with vinegar too. I tried without it just to see if it was necessary, & the paint didn't swirl/spread as easily.
Yep, that, too. I need to get some ornaments and do these again. Maybe next year.
I know, I haven't done it like 15 years, & have been meaning to do it again, after I first saw an article in a craft magazine all those years ago. :)

I did a couple with a friend decades ago, but never since. I keep meaning to, but never do, lol. I've a ton of pins for DIY things for Christmas I'm planning to tackle in the coming months, though, slowly, over time, on my meager budget, lol. The first thing I want to do is the train using crates. It's sooo cute!
